body:
When a Verilog file is synthesized by Yosys, all I/O ports are declared in the alphabetical order. The alphabetical re-ordering can be disturbing when an end-to-end verification tool relies on the specific order of declaration of the ports, e.g., a tool based on [Mockturtle](https://github.com/lsils/mockturtle).

Is there an official way to synthesize the file where the ports are declared in the original order?

## Steps to reproduce the issue

Run a Yosys synthesis command on the source file `ioportnames.v` (see [ioportnames.zip](https://github.com/YosysHQ/yosys/files/8986266/ioportnames.zip)):
```sh
yosys -qp "read_verilog ioportnames.v; synth -auto-top; clean; write_verilog ioportnames_syn.v"
```

## Expected behavior

In the synthesized file `ioportnames_syn.v`, the I/O ports `yankee`, `\november[0]`&ndash;`\november[15]`, and `\alfa[0]`&ndash;`\alfa[15]` should be declared in this order. Within each group of ports, either `november` or `alfa`, the ports should be declared in the numeric order:
```verilog
output [15:0] yankee;
wire [15:0] yankee;
output \november[0] ;
wire \november[0] ;
output \november[1] ;
wire \november[1] ;
output \november[2] ;
wire \november[2] ;
...
output \november[9] ;
wire \november[9] ;
output \november[10] ;
wire \november[10] ;
...
output \november[15] ;
wire \november[15] ;
output \alfa[0] ;
wire \alfa[0] ;
output \alfa[1] ;
wire \alfa[1] ;
output \alfa[2] ;
wire \alfa[2] ;
...
output \alfa[9] ;
wire \alfa[9] ;
output \alfa[10] ;
wire \alfa[10] ;
...
output \alfa[15] ;
wire \alfa[15] ;
```

## Actual behavior

In `ioportnames_syn.v`, `\alfa[0]`&ndash;`\alfa[15]` are followed by `\november[0]`&ndash;`\november[15]` and `yankee`. Furthermore, among `\alfa[0]`&ndash;`\alfa[15]`, `\alfa[10]` is placed before `\alfa[2]`; the same for `november`:
```verilog
output \alfa[0] ;
wire \alfa[0] ;
output \alfa[10] ;
wire \alfa[10] ;
...
output \alfa[15] ;
wire \alfa[15] ;
output \alfa[1] ;
wire \alfa[1] ;
output \alfa[2] ;
wire \alfa[2] ;
...
output \alfa[9] ;
wire \alfa[9] ;
...
output \november[0] ;
wire \november[0] ;
output \november[10] ;
wire \november[10] ;
...
output \november[15] ;
wire \november[15] ;
output \november[1] ;
wire \november[1] ;
output \november[2] ;
wire \november[2] ;
...
output \november[9] ;
wire \november[9] ;
...
output [15:0] yankee;
wire [15:0] yankee;
```

## Acknowledgement

Some of the I/O port names are inspired from the [EPFL benchmarks](https://github.com/lsils/benchmarks).

